 NARRATOR: A few years
 ago, a small town cop

00:43:40.801 --> 00:43:43.400
 would not have gotten
 any professional guidance

00:43:43.501 --> 00:43:46.934
 on how to cope with someone
 appearing to be mentally ill.

00:43:47.033 --> 00:43:50.133
KERBY: Dealing with mentally ill
is a whole different conundrum

00:43:50.234 --> 00:43:52.067
than we've had in the past.

00:43:52.167 --> 00:43:54.234
We didn't understand it,
to be honest with you.

00:43:54.334 --> 00:43:56.000
And I think now there's
so much awareness

00:43:56.100 --> 00:43:58.634
on mental illness,
if we can minimize

00:43:58.734 --> 00:44:01.667
those violent interactions
between law enforcement

00:44:01.767 --> 00:44:03.968
and mentally ill, and get
them the help that they need,

00:44:04.067 --> 00:44:06.434
that's truly what the mission
of helping people's all about.

00:44:06.534 --> 00:44:08.000
JESSE: You know what that
means.

00:44:08.100 --> 00:44:09.801
DEPUTY: But I
just don't want you to put
your hands in your pocket, okay?

00:44:09.901 --> 00:44:11.667
JESSE: I can put my hands in my
pocket any time.

00:44:11.767 --> 00:44:13.133
DEPUTY: Well I don't know what
you have in there.

00:44:13.234 --> 00:44:14.868
Do you have any weapons?

00:44:14.968 --> 00:44:16.534
JESSE: It don't matter if I do
or not.

00:44:16.634 --> 00:44:17.868
DEPUTY: It does matter.

00:44:17.968 --> 00:44:19.334
 NARRATOR: The
 deputies respond

00:44:19.434 --> 00:44:21.000
 just as they've been trained.

00:44:21.100 --> 00:44:23.701
 Take things slow,
 lower your voice,

00:44:23.801 --> 00:44:25.534
 treat it as a
 mental health issue

00:44:25.634 --> 00:44:27.634
 rather than a
 criminal complaint.

00:44:27.734 --> 00:44:28.901
RANDI WEBB: We don't know why
they're not listening,

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:30.567
we don't know why they're
not following commands,

00:44:30.667 --> 00:44:31.901
and there could
be a legit reason

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:33.434
why they're not doing all that.

00:44:33.534 --> 00:44:35.300
And if controlling the situation

00:44:35.400 --> 00:44:37.167
means putting your
hands on somebody,

00:44:37.267 --> 00:44:39.234
you put your hands on somebody.

00:44:39.334 --> 00:44:41.767
DEPUTY: Keep your hands, okay.
JESSE: Hey, whoa, whoa.

00:44:41.868 --> 00:44:43.367
No, what did I do?
DEPUTY: Keep your hands.

00:44:43.467 --> 00:44:44.434
That's like the fourth time

00:44:44.534 --> 00:44:45.567
JESSE: No I didn't.
DEPUTY: I've asked you.

00:44:45.667 --> 00:44:47.334
 NARRATOR: This is not
 an unusual occurrence

00:44:47.434 --> 00:44:48.634
 in rural counties.

00:44:48.734 --> 00:44:50.000
DEPUTY: Hi, are you mom?

00:44:50.100 --> 00:44:52.133
 NARRATOR: Families with
 mentally ill relatives

00:44:52.234 --> 00:44:55.100
 can have frequent visits
 with the local cops.

00:44:55.200 --> 00:44:57.501
MOM: He sees things and
he fights for his life

00:44:57.601 --> 00:44:58.734
and there's--
DEPUTY: Okay.

00:44:58.834 --> 00:44:59.634
MOM: There's nothing there.
DEPUTY: So he'll have like

00:44:59.734 --> 00:45:01.000
an actual fight, just--
MOM: Yes.

00:45:01.100 --> 00:45:02.801
DEPUTY: Nobody there.
MOM: There's nobody there.

00:45:02.901 --> 00:45:03.934
DEPUTY: Okay.

00:45:04.033 --> 00:45:05.334
 NARRATOR: Butler County,
 like most small counties

00:45:05.434 --> 00:45:08.501
 in Nebraska, has no
 mental health specialists,

00:45:08.601 --> 00:45:11.934
 much less beds available
 in area hospitals.

00:45:12.033 --> 00:45:14.534
MOM:
I'm trying to find someplace
else, but I have no money.

00:45:14.634 --> 00:45:16.534
He has no insurance, nothing.

00:45:16.634 --> 00:45:17.601
 NARRATOR: In
 a case like this,

00:45:17.701 --> 00:45:19.434
 the deputies must
 decide if Jesse

00:45:19.534 --> 00:45:22.200
 is a danger to
 himself or others.

00:45:22.300 --> 00:45:23.567
DEPUTY: You burned
yourself, didn't you?

00:45:23.667 --> 00:45:24.901
JESSE: There ain't nothing
wrong.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:26.734
DEPUTY: Okay,
what about your chest?

00:45:26.834 --> 00:45:29.033
JESSE: There is nothing
wrong with me though.

00:45:29.133 --> 00:45:31.434
No, this is it, real shadow.

00:45:31.534 --> 00:45:32.534
What's wrong with that?
What's wrong?

00:45:32.634 --> 00:45:33.200
DEPUTY: See you burned your
chest right there.

00:45:33.300 --> 00:45:34.734
JESSE: That ain't burned.

00:45:34.834 --> 00:45:36.067
No, that ain't burned.

00:45:36.167 --> 00:45:37.334
That's religious stuff.

00:45:37.434 --> 00:45:38.367
DEPUTY: That's religious stuff?
JESSE: Yeah it is for me.

00:45:38.467 --> 00:45:39.200
DEPUTY: Okay.

00:45:39.300 --> 00:45:41.000
JESSE: Hey mom!

00:45:41.100 --> 00:45:44.133
 NARRATOR: Reason enough to
 request he be placed in
 emergency protective custody.

00:45:44.234 --> 00:45:47.734
 It's a long, one-hour drive to
 the crisis center in Lincoln.

00:45:47.834 --> 00:45:49.334
BRENDA URBANEK: It'd be great
if every community

00:45:49.434 --> 00:45:51.367
had a mental health
practitioner,

00:45:51.467 --> 00:45:54.133
that when somebody was
experiencing a crisis,

00:45:54.234 --> 00:45:55.434
we could call them in and say,

00:45:55.534 --> 00:46:00.133
"Hey, we've got him safe right
now, now will you take him?"

00:46:00.234 --> 00:46:03.734
Well anymore, our police
officers on the street

00:46:03.834 --> 00:46:07.033
are having to try to do
initial assessments to see

00:46:07.133 --> 00:46:10.100
what kind of a crisis is
this person experiencing,

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:12.033
and do we have the resources?

00:46:12.133 --> 00:46:13.400
 NARRATOR: At one
 time, Nebraska had

00:46:13.501 --> 00:46:15.100
 regional mental
 health care centers

00:46:15.200 --> 00:46:17.567
 to house the most
 challenging cases.

00:46:17.667 --> 00:46:19.934
 The state re-purposed
 those facilities,

00:46:20.033 --> 00:46:23.167
 shifting most of the long-term
 care responsibilities

00:46:23.267 --> 00:46:24.234
 back to the families.

00:46:24.334 --> 00:46:25.400
MOM: Honey,
I need you to get help.

00:46:25.501 --> 00:46:26.534
JESSE: Can I stay?

00:46:26.634 --> 00:46:27.267
MOM: No, you need help.
JESSE: I'll be okay, mom.

00:46:27.367 --> 00:46:28.033
I was coming home.
MOM: No.

00:46:28.133 --> 00:46:29.000
 NARRATOR: Disturbance calls

00:46:29.100 --> 00:46:31.567
 to local law
 enforcement increased.

00:46:33.033 --> 00:46:36.234
SHERIFF NELS SORENSEN:
Since they closed down
the regional centers here,

00:46:36.334 --> 00:46:43.801
15 years ago or such, their
beds are at a premium.

00:46:43.901 --> 00:46:45.267
 NARRATOR: At the
 Jefferson County jail,

00:46:45.367 --> 00:46:47.334
 deputies brought
 in a man growling

00:46:47.434 --> 00:46:50.667
 and shouting obscenities
 every waking minute.

00:46:50.767 --> 00:46:54.801
 (man screeching)

00:46:54.901 --> 00:46:56.834
SORENSEN: Hours on end.
DISPATCHER: All day.

00:46:56.934 --> 00:46:58.000
 NARRATOR: A judge ordered him

00:46:58.100 --> 00:46:59.968
 sent to the regional center.

00:47:00.133 --> 00:47:04.467
SORENSEN:
He is number 30 on the list
of when a bed comes available,

00:47:04.567 --> 00:47:06.634
so there's 29
people ahead of him

00:47:06.734 --> 00:47:09.133
waiting for a bed at
the regional center.

00:47:09.234 --> 00:47:13.200
So we're, we could
have him for a month,

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:15.601
two months, four months.

00:47:15.701 --> 00:47:19.167
 NARRATOR: The mental illness
 calls, a family in crisis.

00:47:19.267 --> 00:47:20.801
 A potential suicide.

00:47:20.901 --> 00:47:23.701
 Anyone in law enforcement
 who sticks with the job

00:47:23.801 --> 00:47:27.634
 comes to understand a basic
 truth about this kind of work.

00:47:27.734 --> 00:47:28.634
SCHULTZ:
When you're a cop out here,

00:47:28.734 --> 00:47:29.901
you have to learn how
to talk to people.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:31.734
Your greatest weapon
is your mouth.

00:47:31.834 --> 00:47:33.334
And it'll keep you out of a lot

00:47:33.434 --> 00:47:35.667
of fights and
dangerous situations.

00:47:35.767 --> 00:47:39.767
It'll calm things down, it'll
help you stay alive out here.

00:47:39.868 --> 00:47:43.601
OFFICER MANDY MURPHY:
I think a lot of it is just
knowing how to talk to people.

00:47:43.701 --> 00:47:45.634
To talk them down.

00:47:45.734 --> 00:47:47.767
If you can talk to them
and treat them the way

00:47:47.868 --> 00:47:52.834
that you would wanna be treated,
then that gets you a lot.

00:47:52.934 --> 00:47:55.067
SORENSEN: I've always said I've
talked more people to jail

00:47:55.167 --> 00:47:57.434
than I've fought to jail.

00:47:57.534 --> 00:47:59.601
OFFICER CHUCK MENEZES:
Most cops, when they
first get in this job,

00:47:59.701 --> 00:48:01.267
all of us we get
that mentality is,

00:48:01.367 --> 00:48:04.467
we're gonna save people,
and we're gonna go

00:48:04.567 --> 00:48:07.300
arrest all the bad
guys, and take everybody

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:09.033
to jail that needs
to go to jail.

00:48:09.133 --> 00:48:11.200
And there's a certain
point where you realize

00:48:11.300 --> 00:48:12.100
that doesn't always work.

00:48:12.200 --> 00:48:13.267
We've gotta try
to keep them down.

00:48:13.367 --> 00:48:15.434
You can't take
everybody to jail.

00:48:15.534 --> 00:48:18.434
CITIZEN: I have a trap over
at my place too.

00:48:18.534 --> 00:48:21.400
 NARRATOR: Local agencies
hire their own police officers.

00:48:21.501 --> 00:48:24.834
Those recruits train at the Law
 Enforcement Training Center.

00:48:24.934 --> 00:48:27.033
URBANEK: The challenge
we face right now,

00:48:27.133 --> 00:48:28.901
typically we have a class of 50.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:30.701
We only have 40.

00:48:30.801 --> 00:48:34.601
Because agencies are having
difficulty finding applicants

00:48:34.701 --> 00:48:39.167
who meet those standards,
who want to do this job.

00:48:39.267 --> 00:48:40.601
 NARRATOR: Rural
 sheriffs and small town

00:48:40.701 --> 00:48:43.033
 police departments
 face fierce competition

00:48:43.133 --> 00:48:46.000
 for new recruits and
 experienced officers.

00:48:46.100 --> 00:48:48.167
KERBY: When I was hired there
were like 2,000 applicants

00:48:48.267 --> 00:48:50.300
for the 41 jobs that I had.

00:48:50.400 --> 00:48:52.834
Now, agencies are having
a very difficult time

00:48:52.934 --> 00:48:55.868
just finding quality
applicants to come in.

00:48:55.968 --> 00:48:57.501
 NARRATOR: As Butler
 County tried to fill

00:48:57.601 --> 00:49:00.267
 two vacant deputy
 sheriff positions,

00:49:00.367 --> 00:49:05.501
 other agencies had 99 open
 jobs for uniformed officers.

00:49:05.601 --> 00:49:07.434
 (Taser clicking)
OFFICER: It does that.

00:49:07.534 --> 00:49:08.534
Then I can shut it off.

00:49:08.634 --> 00:49:10.901
It's five seconds, and
it's a long five seconds.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.100
OFFICER:
It's a very long five seconds.

00:49:13.200 --> 00:49:15.767
 NARRATOR: It's career night
 at David City High School.

00:49:15.868 --> 00:49:17.000
SIEBKEN: We got
a lotta cool stuff.

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:19.000
We have a lotta technology.

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:20.334
 NARRATOR: Getting
 a small town kid

00:49:20.434 --> 00:49:22.801
 interested in becoming
 a small town cop

00:49:22.901 --> 00:49:25.534
 can become the best
 kind of recruiting.

00:49:25.634 --> 00:49:30.067
SIEBKEN:
With other agencies being
closer to Lincoln and Omaha,

00:49:30.167 --> 00:49:32.033
that's kinda for the
younger generation,

00:49:32.133 --> 00:49:33.400
that's kinda where
they wanna work.

00:49:33.501 --> 00:49:35.067
Being out in rural
Butler County,

00:49:35.167 --> 00:49:38.834
it's hard to find somebody to
come and stay and work here.

00:49:38.934 --> 00:49:39.701
Take a brochure.

00:49:39.801 --> 00:49:41.467
Always keep us in
mind, all right?

00:49:41.567 --> 00:49:43.200
TEEN: Okay.
SIEBKEN: All right.

00:49:43.300 --> 00:49:45.300
 NARRATOR: Average
 salary for a sworn officer

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:49.334
 in central Nebraska runs
 about $50,000 a year.

00:49:49.434 --> 00:49:54.300
 They can earn $13,000
 more by moving to Omaha.

00:49:54.400 --> 00:49:58.033
 That salary is set by county
 boards and city councils.

00:49:58.133 --> 00:50:00.868
 They also decide how many
 officers are on the street

00:50:00.968 --> 00:50:03.601
 every time they pass
 an annual budget.

00:50:03.701 --> 00:50:05.901
SORENSEN: The county board has
given me permission

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:09.767
to hire a single school
resource officer.

00:50:09.868 --> 00:50:11.234
 NARRATOR: Every
 citizen has an opinion

00:50:11.334 --> 00:50:12.667
 about public safety.

00:50:12.767 --> 00:50:15.033
 At election time,
 they get the say

00:50:15.133 --> 00:50:17.567
 on what type of police
 protection they want.

00:50:17.667 --> 00:50:21.100
 2018 was one of those years.

00:50:21.200 --> 00:50:22.934
 In Mitchell, Nebraska,
 there were three

00:50:23.033 --> 00:50:24.701
 candidates for mayor.

00:50:24.801 --> 00:50:29.200
COTANT: Unfortunately, I hate
to say, politics stink.

00:50:29.300 --> 00:50:30.167
They just do.

00:50:30.267 --> 00:50:31.400
 (Train passing by)

00:50:31.501 --> 00:50:32.501
 NARRATOR: Every now and then,

00:50:32.601 --> 00:50:34.300
 somebody gets fired
 up about shutting down

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:36.467
 the police department
 or cutting the budget

00:50:36.567 --> 00:50:39.033
 or changing who's in charge.

00:50:39.133 --> 00:50:42.501
COTANT: So if this year,
when the new mayor,

00:50:42.601 --> 00:50:44.634
or whoever it is
is gonna be mayor,

00:50:44.734 --> 00:50:50.400
decides not to appoint me as
the police chief, I'm done.

00:50:50.501 --> 00:50:52.033
I don't have a job.

00:50:52.133 --> 00:50:54.534
 NARRATOR: Mitchell's incumbent
 mayor wasn't re-elected.

00:50:54.634 --> 00:50:56.501
 There's no sign
 from the new mayor

00:50:56.601 --> 00:51:00.601
 Chief Cotant needs to worry
 about keeping his job.

00:51:00.701 --> 00:51:05.501
 In Jefferson County, Nels
 Sorensen ran unopposed again.

00:51:05.601 --> 00:51:07.734
 He's sheriff for
 another four years.

00:51:07.834 --> 00:51:11.100
SORENSEN:
Little over 3,000 elected
sheriffs in the United States.

00:51:11.200 --> 00:51:13.234
We're a pretty small group.

00:51:13.334 --> 00:51:16.634
Everybody has that
responsibility,

00:51:16.734 --> 00:51:20.000
to the electorate, that
you're doing your job.

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:22.267
And if you're not
doing your job,

00:51:22.367 --> 00:51:25.634
then you're not gonna
be doing it much longer.

00:51:25.734 --> 00:51:26.868
 (plaintive music)

00:51:26.968 --> 00:51:28.334
 NARRATOR: The election
 for sheriff in Butler County

00:51:28.434 --> 00:51:30.033
 took an unexpected turn.

00:51:30.133 --> 00:51:32.634
 After six years in
 office, Marcus Siebken

00:51:32.734 --> 00:51:35.467
 found himself running
 against two opponents.

00:51:35.567 --> 00:51:38.934
MARCUS SIEBKEN:
Obviously, the whole
county looks at the sheriff.

00:51:39.033 --> 00:51:41.300
And that's very hard.

00:51:41.400 --> 00:51:44.601
Just for me personally,
because I hate failure.

00:51:44.701 --> 00:51:47.767
So if I fail, I feel like
I've failed the whole

00:51:47.868 --> 00:51:50.801
area of Butler County, and
I've let every citizen down.

00:51:50.901 --> 00:51:52.868
 BILL KELLY: What does
 failure mean, in this case?

00:51:55.901 --> 00:51:56.901
SIEBKEN: I'm still trying
to figure that out.

00:51:58.968 --> 00:52:00.701
 KELLY: Your
 crime rate hasn't gone up.

00:52:00.801 --> 00:52:02.734
SIEBKEN: No.

00:52:02.834 --> 00:52:08.834
But like I said, I take every
comment, criticism, to heart.

00:52:08.934 --> 00:52:10.300
And that's been the
hardest thing for me

00:52:10.400 --> 00:52:11.767
since I've been sheriff.

00:52:11.868 --> 00:52:15.100
Is because I perceive, when
I go out in the public,

00:52:15.200 --> 00:52:19.534
like my skin is thick and
nothing's gonna hurt me.

00:52:19.634 --> 00:52:23.434
But underneath this uniform,

00:52:23.534 --> 00:52:25.934
this has been a hard
four years for sure.

00:52:26.033 --> 00:52:28.300
 NARRATOR: Butler County
 voters were restless.

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:31.801
 During Siebken's term,
 arrests were up in the county,

00:52:31.901 --> 00:52:33.934
 but there were complaints
 before the election

00:52:34.033 --> 00:52:38.501
 about locals getting too many
 speeding tickets and DUI's.

00:52:38.601 --> 00:52:40.133
SIEBKEN: You know, being in
a small community,

00:52:40.234 --> 00:52:45.000
a lot of people do expect
the good ol' boy system yet,

00:52:45.100 --> 00:52:47.367
and expect a favor
here and there.

00:52:47.467 --> 00:52:51.801
And I always said,
if I lose an election

00:52:51.901 --> 00:52:55.033
because I did the right
thing, then so be it.

00:52:55.133 --> 00:52:57.100
That's not who I am,
I treat everybody fair,

00:52:57.200 --> 00:53:00.100
and we're not gonna hide
anything from anybody.

00:53:01.834 --> 00:53:04.100
 NARRATOR: Marcus
 Siebken lost the election.

00:53:04.200 --> 00:53:06.501
 He has since taken
 a better-paying job

00:53:06.601 --> 00:53:08.601
 outside of law enforcement.

00:53:08.701 --> 00:53:11.000
SORENSEN: If you're making
everybody happy,

00:53:11.100 --> 00:53:12.934
I've always said you're
not doing your job.

00:53:13.033 --> 00:53:16.367
So there's somebody not
gonna be happy with you.

00:53:16.467 --> 00:53:18.000
I think the big
thing is, is that

00:53:18.100 --> 00:53:20.067
you're answerable to the public.

00:53:20.167 --> 00:53:23.200
I think that's what
America's all about.

00:53:23.300 --> 00:53:26.534
 NARRATOR: Elections,
recruiting, changes in the job.

00:53:26.634 --> 00:53:29.567
 All of that is in the
 background on graduation day

00:53:29.667 --> 00:53:32.400
 at the Law Enforcement
 Training Center.

00:53:32.501 --> 00:53:35.367
 Eagerness and apprehension
 fills the room.

00:53:35.467 --> 00:53:38.934
 Families born of generations
 of law enforcement officers

00:53:39.033 --> 00:53:40.767
 gather around the rookies.

00:53:40.868 --> 00:53:42.501
 KELLY: Did your dad
 ever sit you down and say,

00:53:42.601 --> 00:53:44.167
 "Do you really wanna do this?"

00:53:44.267 --> 00:53:45.934
DEPUTY ZACH KRAMER:
A couple times, yeah.

00:53:46.033 --> 00:53:47.734
 KELLY: Tell me
 about that conversation.

00:53:47.834 --> 00:53:49.400
KRAMER: Well, I guess you
could say I'm stubborn

00:53:49.501 --> 00:53:52.033
and just didn't listen, but.
 (Father laughs)

00:53:52.133 --> 00:53:55.534
COMMANDER: Forward march.

00:53:55.634 --> 00:53:59.133
URBANEK: A successful graduate
is somebody who recognizes

00:53:59.234 --> 00:54:00.467
that you have to have compassion

00:54:00.567 --> 00:54:02.400
for your fellow human being,

00:54:02.501 --> 00:54:05.234
whether it's a
suspect or a victim.

00:54:05.334 --> 00:54:06.701
 PRESENTER:
 Deputy Zach Kramer,

00:54:06.801 --> 00:54:08.200
 Lincoln County
 Sheriff's Office.

00:54:08.300 --> 00:54:10.300
URBANEK: The successful
graduate, even though they walk

00:54:10.400 --> 00:54:14.334
across that stage and get that
packet with their diploma,

00:54:14.434 --> 00:54:16.968
realizes, "I don't
know anything yet.

00:54:17.067 --> 00:54:18.234
"I gotta keep learning."

00:54:19.767 --> 00:54:24.400
KRAMER: Be aware that you have
chosen a very dangerous career.

00:54:24.501 --> 00:54:26.634
At some point, someone
is going to try

00:54:26.734 --> 00:54:29.200
to hurt you or kill you.

00:54:29.300 --> 00:54:30.534
Keep that in mind every day,

00:54:30.634 --> 00:54:33.901
and keep in mind
that you will win.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:36.267
You never lose.

00:54:36.367 --> 00:54:38.300
URBANEK: A successful
graduate is somebody

00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:41.300
who recognizes that they
are entering a profession

00:54:41.400 --> 00:54:44.601
which is noble and honorable,

00:54:44.701 --> 00:54:46.534
that they have to
have that integrity

00:54:46.634 --> 00:54:49.067
throughout their career.

00:54:49.167 --> 00:54:51.100
Once they lose that integrity,

00:54:51.200 --> 00:54:53.934
they should go sell
shoes or something.

00:54:54.033 --> 00:54:55.934
 NARRATOR: Once all the
 certificates are issued,

00:54:56.033 --> 00:54:59.501
 they turn to the audience and
 deliver the Academy's Oath.

00:54:59.601 --> 00:55:00.601
ALL OFFICERS:
Honor, integrity,

00:55:00.701 --> 00:55:02.434
and respect are never betrayed.

00:55:02.534 --> 00:55:05.100
 NARRATOR: Within days,
 they are on full duty,

00:55:05.200 --> 00:55:07.400
 many serving in
 counties and towns

00:55:07.501 --> 00:55:11.133
 with populations smaller than
 single neighborhoods in Omaha.

00:55:11.234 --> 00:55:13.200
OFFICER: How you doing buddy?
OFFICER: Pretty good.

00:55:13.300 --> 00:55:14.501
 NARRATOR: Out
 in the panhandle,

00:55:14.601 --> 00:55:17.467
 Officer Preston brought the
 Mitchell Police Department

00:55:17.567 --> 00:55:19.934
 back to full strength.

00:55:20.033 --> 00:55:22.601
PRESTON:
My family never discouraged
me from doing something

00:55:22.701 --> 00:55:23.868
that I felt like I wanted to do,

00:55:23.968 --> 00:55:27.367
and I'm not gonna discourage
somebody else from doing it.

00:55:27.467 --> 00:55:28.367
It's scary.

00:55:28.467 --> 00:55:30.901
The times are getting
even more scarier.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:32.734
Going through the training,
and being told things

00:55:32.834 --> 00:55:37.667
that we were told, and doing
what we did, and it is scary.

00:55:37.767 --> 00:55:38.968
 It'll be a 1983...

00:55:39.067 --> 00:55:41.200
I think if you have a heart
for people to do your job

00:55:41.300 --> 00:55:44.167
and to uphold the law,
then I think it's okay.

00:55:44.267 --> 00:55:45.767
I think you'll be fine.

00:55:45.868 --> 00:55:48.200
 You gotta do what
 you gotta do, Steve!

00:55:48.300 --> 00:55:50.400
It's nice to work
in a smaller town,

00:55:50.501 --> 00:55:52.133
because you can have
the rapport with people

00:55:52.234 --> 00:55:53.367
and people can trust you.

00:55:53.467 --> 00:55:56.334
They know that they
don't have to worry

00:55:56.434 --> 00:55:58.400
so much during the day.

00:55:58.501 --> 00:55:59.434
I love it here.

00:55:59.534 --> 00:56:02.100
I don't wanna work
in a big city.

00:56:02.200 --> 00:56:04.000
I like it here.

